[2] Pennsylvania, 2 cats, 1 person
Date: Fri 11 Nov 2016
Source: Lehigh Valley Live [edited]
http://www.lehighvalleylive.com/bethlehem/index.ssf/2016/11/rabies_confirmed_in_cats_in_lo.html


Rabies confirmed in cats in Lower Saucon Township, Northampton County [Pennsylvania]
---------------------------------------------------------------------
Two cases of rabies in cats have been confirmed recently in Lower Saucon Township, according to police there. Both have been in the area of Dartford Road, off Black River Road, and one resident was bitten by one of the rabid felines, township police said in a news release on Thursday night [10 Nov 2016]. [See source URL for a map of the area showing where cats were recovered. - Mod.MHJ]

[Clinical] rabies is nearly always fatal, the US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention [CDC] says. Strays or unwanted animals that attack a person or pet should be confined and observed for 10 days or be euthanized and tested for rabies immediately. The latter goes for skunks, raccoons, foxes and bats that bite humans, says CDC.

According to township police: "There are 2 common types of rabies in cats. Furious rabies is characterized by extreme behavioral changes, including overt aggression and attack behavior. Paralytic rabies, also referred to as dumb rabies, is characterized by weakness and loss of coordination in the cat, followed by paralysis." Police advise townships residents who encounter a cat behaving strangely to stay away from it and call the department. Police may be reached via 911 or the Northampton County dispatch non-emergency line at 610-759-2200. Rabies is spread through saliva or brain/nervous system tissue, the CDC says. Anyone bitten by an unfamiliar or wild animal is urged to wash any wounds immediately and seek medical treatment for any trauma due to the attack before considering the need for rabies prophylaxis.

Post-exposure vaccination consists of 5 doses administered in the arm, like a flu or tetanus vaccine.

[byline: Kurt Bresswein]

