[For a map of South Carolina showing Florence County in east central SC, go to http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/states/south_carolina.gif. For Northampton County, Pennsylvania, on the eastern border with New Jersey, go to http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/states/pennsylvania.gif. For Weld County, Colorado, on the northern border with Wyoming, go to http://www.lib.utexas.edu/maps/states/colorado.gif or https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weld_County,_Colorado.

With 3 reports, flush with advice, I will limit myself to the obvious. Make sure your pet dogs and cats are vaccinated, and don't mess with sick animals which are not your own and especially wildlife. If you suspect a case, call the police. They know what to do and whom to call in to catch the animal. If you are bitten or scratched, go to emergency health ASAP. If the animal is confirmed rabid, you should be contacted in order to make sure you have been vaccinated. As a field veterinarian, I used to ensure I was regularly vaccinated every 3 years as I never knew when I might knowingly or unknowingly meet up with a rabid bat, skunk, whatever, and over the years I have, starting with a colony of infected Mexican free-tailed bats in a slave quarter in the New Orleans [Louisiana, USA] French Quarter when I was a grad student. They were in the ceiling space above a 4 inch [10cm] layer of bat guano that I had cut up through. I now have a good antibody titre which my doctor checks routinely. - Mod.MHJ

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=4623340,209.]
